   613	  CREATE INDEX idx_callback_tokens_approval ON callback_tokens(approval_id);
   614	  CREATE INDEX idx_callback_tokens_status_expires
   615	    ON callback_tokens(status, expires_at);
   616	  ```
   617	
   618	  Token storage policy:
   619	
   620	  ```text
   621	  raw_token  = base32(crypto.randomBytes(10))[:16]  ← 16 chars, ≥80 bits
   622	                                                     entropy. NEVER
   623	                                                     stored.
   624	  token_hash = sha256(raw_token).slice(0, 32)       ← stored as PRIMARY
   625	                                                     KEY. SQLite leak
   626	                                                     does not compromise
   627	                                                     in-flight callbacks.
   628	  callback_data on the wire = "v1:" + raw_token    ← only the IM
   629	                                                     platform sees the
   630	                                                     raw token, in the
   631	                                                     callback only.
   632	  ```
   633	
   634	  Status transitions are atomic single-row UPDATEs with `WHERE status = ?`
   635	  guards. Used-token replay (race between two simultaneous clicks)
   636	  fails closed because the second UPDATE returns 0 rows changed.
   637	
   638	  **Target hydration contract** (★ v2.4 P1-4 ★). The `Target` shape
   639	  (`{platform, chatId, threadKey?, topicId?}`) is stored as four
   640	  explicit columns (`target_platform`, `target_chat_id`,
   641	  `target_thread_key`, `target_topic_id`), NOT as a single derived
   642	  `target_key` string. `CallbackTokenRepository` hydrates
   643	  `CallbackTokenRecord.target: Target` by reading these 4 columns:
   644	
   645	  ```ts
   646	  // packages/storage-sqlite/src/callback-tokens.ts (Phase 3 T6d)
   647	  function hydrate(row: CallbackTokenRow): CallbackTokenRecord {
   648	    return {
   649	      tokenHash: row.token_hash,
   650	      approvalId: row.approval_id,
   651	      action: row.action,
   652	      callbackNonce: row.callback_nonce,
   653	      target: {
   654	        platform:  row.target_platform,
   655	        chatId:    row.target_chat_id,
   656	        threadKey: row.target_thread_key  ?? undefined,
   657	        topicId:   row.target_topic_id    ?? undefined,
   658	      },
   659	      // ... actor_*, msg_*, status, timestamps
   660	    };
   661	  }
   662	  ```
   663	
   664	  Why explicit columns instead of a derived `target_key`: wrong-target
   665	  validation (T-Sec-3) deep-equals the hydrated `Target` against the
   666	  inbound `action.target`. A composite delimiter-separated string would
   667	  require a parser (delimiter-conflict bug surface, optional-field
   668	  encoding rules); explicit columns let SQLite + TypeScript do the
   669	  typing. T6d adds a round-trip test (insert with full `Target`,
   670	  hydrate, deep-equal). §10.3 step 3 uses the hydrated record:
   671	  `record.target.platform === action.target.platform &&
   672	  record.target.chatId === action.target.chatId && ...`.
   673	
   674	- **D35 (v2 NEW)** — MessageRef validation before `broker.resolve`.
   675	  `InboundAction` (`packages/channel-core/src/types.ts`) is extended

 succeeded in 0ms:
   757	- **D38 (v2 NEW, supersedes D23)** — `SessionRouter` synchronous
   758	  write-through. v1's "async write-through" conflicted with G3
   759	  (binding restart-survival). v2 contract:
   760	
   761	  ```text
   762	  router.bind(target, projectId)   ← synchronous SQLite UPSERT
   763	                                     before return; on write failure,
   764	                                     throws; in-memory cache NOT
   765	                                     updated.
   766	  router.bindThread(target, threadId) ← same sync pattern.
   767	  router.resolve(target)           ← in-memory cache hit (fast);
   768	                                     cache miss → sync SQLite read,
   769	                                     populate cache, return.
   770	  ```
   771	
   772	  `/use`, `/new` slash commands MUST `await router.bind()` (or
   773	  `bindThread`) before sending the user-facing acknowledgement
   774	  message. SQLite write failure → command fails with operator-readable
   775	  error; binding NOT silently lost.
   776	
   777	- **D39 (v2 NEW)** — SQLite native preflight + fallback policy.
   778	  T1 begins with:
   779	
   780	  ```bash
   781	  pnpm add better-sqlite3 kysely
   782	  node -e 'const db = require("better-sqlite3")(":memory:"); \
   783	    db.prepare("select 1 as x").get(); console.log("better-sqlite3 ok");'
   784	  ```
   785	
   786	  If preflight passes: proceed with `better-sqlite3`. Storage tasks
   787	  unblocked.
   788	
   789	  If preflight fails: STOP. Storage tasks blocked. The user decides
   790	  between two paths:
   791	  - (a) Try Node 24's built-in `node:sqlite` as a fallback CANDIDATE,
   792	    AFTER a separate preflight that proves both (i) the sync API
   793	    needed by D34/D38 is supported on the running Node version and
   794	    (ii) all storage-sqlite tests pass against `node:sqlite`. **Note**
   795	    per Node docs `node:sqlite` is currently release-candidate /
   796	    active-development; treat as preflight-required, not a free
   797	    swap-in.
   798	  - (b) Abort the storage sliver; re-scope Phase 3 to defer SessionRouter
   799	    persistence to Phase 4 (G3 acceptance criterion would not be met).

